# Git Workflow (solo-first, trunk-based)

Default assumption: a single-maintainer repo where the author both writes and
merges the change. Speculative branches add integration cost with no review
benefit here.

## Branching

- Commit directly to the current working branch (usually `main`). Do NOT create
  a feature branch or git worktree by default.
- Create a branch ONLY when one of these is true: a real collaborator/PR is in
  the loop, the change is a long-lived experiment that must not touch `main`, or
  the user explicitly asks for a branch.
- Never create a branch "just in case". A branch only the author will merge back
  is pure integration overhead.
- Leave the repo on the branch you started on. Do not end a task on a detached
  HEAD or an orphaned worktree.

## Safety without branches

- Replace the branch-as-safety-net habit with the executable check: run
  lint + build (and tests if present) before committing to `main`.
- If there is no runnable check and the change is risky, say so and propose the
  smallest check to add, rather than hiding the work on a branch.

## Commits

- One logical change per commit. Do not bundle unrelated edits.
- Conventional, imperative commit subjects in English (e.g. `fix: guard null
  session before render`).
- Do not commit secrets, `.env` files, or generated artifacts. If they are
  already tracked, flag it instead of committing more.
